    summary: "Given the root of a binary tree, find the minimum number of edges from the root to any leaf node (a node with no children), returning 0 for an empty tree.",
    approach: "- Use BFS (level-order traversal) so the very first leaf encountered is guaranteed to be at the shallowest depth.\n- Track the current depth alongside each node as it enters the queue.\n- The moment we dequeue a node that has no left or right child, that depth is the answer — return it immediately without scanning the rest of the tree.\n- This early-exit property makes BFS preferable to DFS for minimum depth: DFS must traverse all paths to compare, whereas BFS naturally stops at the first leaf.",
    code: "#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nstruct TreeNode {\n    int val;\n    TreeNode *left;\n    TreeNode *right;\n    TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}\n};\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int minDepth(TreeNode* root) {\n        if (!root) return 0;\n\n        // BFS: each entry is (node, depth). The first leaf we pop is\n        // at the minimum depth — return immediately.\n        queue<pair<TreeNode*, int>> q;\n        q.push({root, 1});\n\n        while (!q.empty()) {\n            auto [node, depth] = q.front();\n            q.pop();\n\n            // A leaf has no children — this is the shallowest such node.\n            if (!node->left && !node->right) return depth;\n\n            if (node->left)  q.push({node->left,  depth + 1});\n            if (node->right) q.push({node->right, depth + 1});\n        }\n\n        return 0; // unreachable for non-empty input\n    }\n};\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(n) — each node is enqueued and dequeued at most once, though in the best case (left-skewed or balanced) we exit well before visiting all nodes.",
