    approach: "- Perform a single post-order DFS so that each node receives the height of its left and right subtrees before computing its own contribution.\n- At each node, the diameter candidate passing through that node equals `leftHeight + rightHeight` (edges going down both sides).\n- Track the global maximum diameter in an integer reference as the recursion unwinds, and return height (`max(left, right) + 1`) up the call stack.\n- This one-pass traversal avoids redundant recomputation that would occur if height and diameter were computed separately.",
    code: "#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\n// Definition for a binary tree node.\nstruct TreeNode {\n    int val;\n    TreeNode *left;\n    TreeNode *right;\n    TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}\n};\n\nclass Solution {\n    // Returns the height of the subtree rooted at node (number of edges to deepest leaf).\n    // Updates `best` with the longest diameter seen so far.\n    int height(TreeNode* node, int& best) {\n        if (!node) return 0;\n\n        int leftH  = height(node->left,  best);\n        int rightH = height(node->right, best);\n\n        // Diameter through this node = edges going left + edges going right.\n        best = max(best, leftH + rightH);\n\n        return max(leftH, rightH) + 1;\n    }\n\npublic:\n    int diameterOfBinaryTree(TreeNode* root) {\n        int best = 0;\n        height(root, best);\n        return best;\n    }\n};",
