    approach: "- Perform a DFS traversal, passing down the current streak length and the parent's value at each step.\n- At each node, extend the streak by 1 if the node's value equals parent + 1; otherwise reset the streak to 1.\n- Track the global maximum streak seen so far via a reference parameter, updating it after each node is processed.\n- This works because consecutive sequences can only grow downward (parent to child), so a single top-down pass visits every possible streak exactly once in O(n) time.",
    code: "#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\n// Definition for a binary tree node.\nstruct TreeNode {\n    int val;\n    TreeNode *left;\n    TreeNode *right;\n    TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}\n    TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}\n};\n\nclass Solution {\n    // DFS helper: parentVal is the value of the calling node,\n    // streak is the current consecutive length, maxLen tracks the global best.\n    void dfs(TreeNode* node, int parentVal, int streak, int& maxLen) {\n        if (!node) return;\n\n        // Extend streak if consecutive, otherwise restart at 1.\n        streak = (node->val == parentVal + 1) ? streak + 1 : 1;\n        maxLen = max(maxLen, streak);\n\n        dfs(node->left,  node->val, streak, maxLen);\n        dfs(node->right, node->val, streak, maxLen);\n    }\n\npublic:\n    int longestConsecutive(TreeNode* root) {\n        int maxLen = 0;\n        // Seed parentVal as root->val - 1 so the root always starts a streak of 1.\n        if (root) dfs(root, root->val - 1, 0, maxLen);\n        return maxLen;\n    }\n};\n",
