    approach: "- Use three arrays of nine bitmasks — one per row, one per column, one per 3x3 box — to track which digits have been seen.\n- For each non-empty cell, compute the digit (0-indexed) and the box index `(row/3)*3 + col/3`, then check all three corresponding bitmasks for a collision.\n- If any digit is already recorded in the same row, column, or box, return `false`; otherwise set the corresponding bit and continue.\n- Because the board is always exactly 81 cells, every loop is bounded by a constant, making the overall work O(1).",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <array>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool isValidSudoku(vector<vector<char>>& board) {\n        // Each entry is a bitmask for digits 1-9 (bit i-1 represents digit i)\n        array<int, 9> rows{}, cols{}, boxes{};\n\n        for (int r = 0; r < 9; ++r) {\n            for (int c = 0; c < 9; ++c) {\n                if (board[r][c] == '.') continue;\n\n                int digit = board[r][c] - '1';   // 0-indexed digit\n                int mask   = 1 << digit;\n                int box    = (r / 3) * 3 + (c / 3);\n\n                // Collision in row, column, or box?\n                if ((rows[r] & mask) || (cols[c] & mask) || (boxes[box] & mask))\n                    return false;\n\n                rows[r]    |= mask;\n                cols[c]    |= mask;\n                boxes[box] |= mask;\n            }\n        }\n        return true;\n    }\n};",
