    approach: "- Use a 1-D DP array `dp` of size `amount + 1`, where `dp[a]` stores the number of ways to make amount `a`.\n- Base case: `dp[0] = 1` (one way to make zero — use no coins).\n- For each coin, iterate through all amounts from `coin` to `amount`, adding `dp[a - coin]` to `dp[a]`. Processing one coin at a time ensures each combination is counted once (order-independent), avoiding permutation duplicates.\n- Final answer is `dp[amount]`.",
    code: "#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int change(int amount, vector<int>& coins) {\n        // dp[a] = number of distinct combinations summing to a\n        vector<int> dp(amount + 1, 0);\n        dp[0] = 1; // one way to reach zero: pick nothing\n\n        // outer loop over coins keeps each combination order-independent\n        for (int coin : coins) {\n            for (int a = coin; a <= amount; ++a) {\n                dp[a] += dp[a - coin];\n            }\n        }\n\n        return dp[amount];\n    }\n};\n",
