    approach: "- Track `maxReach`, the farthest index reachable so far.\n- At each index `i`, if `i > maxReach` the position is unreachable and we immediately return `false`.\n- Otherwise, update `maxReach = max(maxReach, i + nums[i])`.\n- If `maxReach` ever reaches or exceeds the last index, return `true`; if the loop ends without doing so, return `false`. This greedy strategy works because extending the reach greedily never sacrifices future options.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool canJump(vector<int>& nums) {\n        int maxReach = 0;                        // farthest index we can currently reach\n        int last = (int)nums.size() - 1;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i <= last; ++i) {\n            if (i > maxReach) return false;      // current index is unreachable\n            maxReach = max(maxReach, i + nums[i]);\n            if (maxReach >= last) return true;   // can already reach the end\n        }\n\n        return true;  // last index was reachable throughout the loop\n    }\n};\n",
