    routeSlug: "62-unique-paths",
    summary: "Given an m x n grid, count the number of distinct paths from the top-left corner to the bottom-right corner, where only rightward and downward moves are allowed.",
    approach: "- At any cell (r, c), the number of ways to reach it equals the sum of ways from the cell above and the cell to the left, since those are the only two predecessors.\n- The top row and left column are base cases: exactly one path reaches any cell along either edge (only one direction of travel is possible).\n- We can compress the 2-D DP table to a single 1-D row: iterating left-to-right, `dp[col] += dp[col-1]` accumulates the \"from-left\" contribution in-place while `dp[col]` (before update) still holds the \"from-above\" value.\n- The answer is `dp[n-1]` after processing all m rows.",
    code: "#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int uniquePaths(int m, int n) {\n        // dp[c] = number of unique paths to reach the current row at column c.\n        // Initialize to 1: the first row has exactly one path to each cell.\n        vector<int> dp(n, 1);\n\n        // Process rows 1..m-1; row 0 is already handled by the initialization.\n        for (int r = 1; r < m; ++r) {\n            // col 0 always has exactly 1 path (move straight down), no update needed.\n            for (int c = 1; c < n; ++c) {\n                // dp[c]   currently holds \"paths from above\" (previous row, same col)\n                // dp[c-1] holds \"paths from the left\" (same row, previous col, already updated)\n                dp[c] += dp[c - 1];\n            }\n        }\n\n        return dp[n - 1];\n    }\n};\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(m * n)",
    spaceComplexity: "O(n)",
