    approach: "- Compress the string into run-length groups: track how many consecutive identical characters appear in each contiguous run.\n- For every adjacent pair of runs, `min(run[i], run[i+1])` substrings of the required form can be formed, because the shorter run is the bottleneck.\n- Keep only the previous run count to avoid the auxiliary vector, reducing space to O(1).\n- A single linear scan suffices, making the algorithm O(n) time.",
    code: "#include <string>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int countBinarySubstrings(string s) {\n        int result = 0;\n        int prev = 0;       // length of the run before the current one\n        int cur  = 1;       // length of the current run\n\n        for (int i = 1; i < (int)s.size(); ++i) {\n            if (s[i] == s[i - 1]) {\n                ++cur;\n            } else {\n                // Transition: the previous run is now fully known\n                prev = cur;\n                cur  = 1;\n            }\n            // At every position, if prev >= cur there is a valid substring\n            // ending here (cur chars of one kind + cur chars of the other).\n            if (prev >= cur) ++result;\n        }\n\n        return result;\n    }\n};",
